## Theorem: translated_imo_2004_p5

Theorem: translated_imo_2004_p5
Given: a b c = triangle a b c
Given: o = circle o a b c
Given: d = on_circle d o a
Given: p = on_aline p b c a b d, on_aline p d c a d b
Prove: prove that segment ap = segment cp

Goal: cong a p c p

## English proof (from stage 1)
{
  "key_observation": "Because A, B, C, D are concyclic, the angle conditions defining P can be rewritten as angle conditions involving the chord AC, and these force P to lie on the perpendicular bisector of AC.",
  "plan": [
    "Use the fact that D lies on the circumcircle of triangle ABC to obtain cyclic angle equalities.",
    "Rewrite the two defining angle-line conditions for P using those cyclic angle equalities.",
    "Apply the standard cyclic angle-line lemma showing that such a point P lies on the perpendicular bisector of AC.",
    "Conclude that PA = PC."
  ],
  "steps": [
    {
      "claim": "The four points A, B, C, D are concyclic.",
      "reasoning": "The circle o passes through A, B, and C by the hypothesis that o is the circumcircle of triangle ABC. The point D also lies on o, so A, B, C, D all lie on the same circle.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of circumcircle",
        "definition of on_circle"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "∠ABD = ∠ACD and ∠ADB = ∠ACB.",
      "reasoning": "In a cyclic quadrilateral, inscribed angles subtending the same chord are equal. The angles ∠ABD and ∠ACD both subtend chord AD, while ∠ADB and ∠ACB both subtend chord AB.",
      "facts_used": [
        "inscribed angle theorem",
        "step 1"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The defining conditions for P imply ∠PBC = ∠ACD and ∠PDC = ∠ACB.",
      "reasoning": "By the meaning of the two angle-line conditions, P satisfies ∠PBC = ∠ABD and ∠PDC = ∠ADB. Substituting the cyclic angle equalities from step 2 gives ∠PBC = ∠ACD and ∠PDC = ∠ACB.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of on_aline",
        "step 2"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "If A, B, C, D are concyclic and a point P satisfies ∠PBC = ∠ACD and ∠PDC = ∠ACB, then P lies on the perpendicular bisector of AC.",
      "reasoning": "This is the standard cyclic angle-line lemma. One proof is to normalize by a similarity so that A = (-1,0) and C = (1,0). Then the common circle has equation x^2 + y^2 - 2ty = 1. Writing B = (u,v), D = (r,s), and P = (x,y), the two angle equalities translate into two linear equations in x and y via the tangent formula for the angle between two lines. Using the circle equations for B and D, subtracting the two resulting linear relations cancels the y-terms and gives x = 0. Thus P lies on the line x = 0, which is exactly the perpendicular bisector of AC.",
      "facts_used": [
        "standard cyclic angle-line lemma",
        "analytic geometry",
        "tangent formula for angle between two lines"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "PA = PC.",
      "reasoning": "Every point on the perpendicular bisector of a segment is equidistant from the endpoints of that segment. Since P lies on the perpendicular bisector of AC, it follows that PA = PC.",
      "facts_used": [
        "perpendicular bisector theorem",
        "step 4"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "final_answer": null
}

